  "prompt": "My one-year-old doesn't eat any vegetables or meat, but only pieces of bread and fruits. What should I do?",
  "response": "Here are some strategies to help expand your child's diet:\n\n1. Gradual introduction\n- Introduce new foods slowly\n- Mix vegetables into foods they already like\n- Offer small portions of new foods repeatedly\n\n2. Make food fun and attractive\n- Cut vegetables into interesting shapes\n- Use colorful plates\n- Make meals visually appealing\n\n3. Lead by example\n- Eat vegetables and meat in front of them\n- Show enthusiasm while eating\n- Let them see you enjoying different foods\n\n4. Presentation techniques\n- Blend vegetables into smoothies\n- Mix pureed vegetables into sauces or baked goods\n- Try different cooking methods (roasting, steaming)\n\n5. Involve them in food preparation\n- Let them help in the kitchen\n- Let them choose vegetables at the store\n- Make cooking a fun activity\n\n6. Nutritional considerations\n- Ensure they're getting balanced nutrients\n- Consult pediatrician about potential supplements\n- Consider vitamin-rich alternatives\n\n7. Be patient\n- Don't force food\n- Avoid making mealtimes stressful\n- Understand that food preferences change\n\n8. Consider texture variations\n- Some children dislike certain textures\n- Try different preparations (raw, cooked, mashed)\n\nRemember, every child is different, and persistence is key.",
